# The objective - 
- To find the password for LEVEL9. The password is stored in a file called data.txt in the home directory. The password is the only line in the file that appears only once.

# The commands you used - 
- ssh udername@hostname -p <port>
- ls
- cat data.txt
- sort data.txt | uniq -u


# Why your solution worked - 
-  First, I checked the files available in the directory: ls
- On reading the file using the cat command, i found that data.txt file had many lines of text, but manually finding the unique line would be inefficient.
- sort data.txt - Sorts all lines in the file alphabetically. This is required because uniq only detects duplicate lines that are next to each other. Sorting groups identical lines together.
- The pipe operator sends the output of one command as input to another command.
- uniq is used to detect or remove repeated lines from text.
    uniq → Removes consecutive duplicate lines and prints only one copy of each repeated line.
    uniq -c → Counts how many times each line appears.
    uniq -u → Displays only lines that appear once.
- sort data.txt | uniq -u  allowed me to Arrange identical lines together using sort. Filter out repeated lines and display only the unique line using uniq -u. The remaining line was the password for Bandit Level 8.


# Key Linux concepts or commands you learned - 
- sort arranges lines of text in a specific order, usually alphabetically.
It is often used before commands like uniq because duplicate detection requires identical lines to be adjacent.
- uniq is used to detect or remove repeated lines from text.
Common options:
uniq → Removes consecutive duplicate lines.
uniq -c → Counts how many times each line appears.
uniq -u → Displays only lines that appear once.
- The pipe operator connects commands together by passing the output of one command into another.
